{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486608"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/142"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.09,0.04,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110096"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92394"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1241"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3679"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4748"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37217"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110096"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of a painless urethral discharge. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He reports several unprotected sexual encounters with female partners over the last few weeks. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The only abnormal physical finding is a small quantity of purulent material visible at the urethral meatus. A urethral swab is collected for gonococcal culture and returns positive for \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. First-pass urine nucleic acid amplification test (NAAT) is negative for \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Single dose of intramuscular ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin","Doxycycline twice daily for one week","Oral ciprofloxacin twice daily for five days","Single dose of oral azithromycin","Single dose of intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the most recent guidelines, the recommended treatment for uncomplicated genital gonorrhoea is a \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle dose of intramuscular ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin.\u003C/strong\u003E This dual antibiotic therapy is now recommended to counteract the emerging resistance to ceftriaxone that has been observed in \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline twice daily for one weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not the recommended regimen for gonorrhoea. Doxycycline is given for 7 days for treatment of chlamydia however is not used in the treatment of gonorrhoea. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer recommended as first-line treatment for gonorrhoea due to widespread resistance. It may still be used in some cases if antimicrobial susceptibility testing shows the isolate is sensitive, but this is not routine practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose of oral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is used as part of dual therapy for gonorrhoea, but is no longer recommended as monotherapy due to increasing resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose of intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective against \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E and is not used in the treatment of gonorrhoea. It\u0027s primarily used for the treatment of syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotic treatment, the patient should be advised to abstain from sexual activity for 7 days following treatment completion. Contact tracing of sexual partners from the last 2 months should be performed, and these contacts should be tested and treated empirically. It\u0027s also important to retest for gonorrhoea 3 months after treatment to ensure cure and detect any reinfection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uncomplicated gonorrhoea should be treated with IM ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin","Dual therapy for gonorrhoea helps combat antimicrobial resistance"],"references":["Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine (ASHM). Gonorrhoea. In: Australian STI Management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care [Internet]. Sydney: ASHM; [updated 2023; cited 2025 Jul 27]. Available from: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/gonorrhoea","Unemo M. Current and future antimicrobial treatment of gonorrhoea - the rapidly evolving Neisseria gonorrhoeae continues to challenge. BMC Infect Dis. 2015 Aug 21;15:364. doi: 10.1186/s12879-015-1029-2. PMID: 26293005; PMCID: PMC4546108. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26293005/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92394"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92394"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T11:36:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T11:36:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"142"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110096"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1241"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Urethral swab","synonyms":["Urethral culture","Urethr